actor1: ASWJ-Mozambique: Ahlu Sunna Wal Jamaa (Mozambique faction)
source: Club of Mozambique; Agence France Presse; Agencia de Informacao de Mocambique
notes: Armed gunmen associated with an Islamist fundamentalist group attacked civilians at Mitumbate/Mutumbati and Makulo/Megulo villages in Mocimboa da Praia on 29 and 30 November, killing two, wounding another two, burning 27 houses and destroying a church. The fundamentalist group is composed of Mozambicans, but also Tanzanians and Somalis and is suspected to be the same as the 5-6 October attacks in Mocimboa.

actor2: ASWJ-Mozambique: Ahlu Sunna Wal Jamaa (Mozambique faction)
notes: On the week of 12 March, 2 rebels were killed by the police forces in Mocimboa da Praia.

actor1: ASWJ-Mozambique: Ahlu Sunna Wal Jamaa (Mozambique faction)
notes: Property destruction: following the attack in Olumbi, the same militia attacked the locality of Quissenge, burning 32 houses and 3 informal shops.

actor2: ASWJ-Mozambique: Ahlu Sunna Wal Jamaa (Mozambique faction)
source: Agence France Presse; Agencia de Informacao de Mocambique
notes: Arrests: Police forces in Mozambique arrest 52 people after the attacks in the last week in Mocimboa da Praia. Authorities have dismissed links of linkage to Somalia's Al-Shabab or Nigeria's Boko Haram. Another 75 people were arrested a month later, on 1 November.

actor2: ASWJ-Mozambique: Ahlu Sunna Wal Jamaa (Mozambique faction)
notes: An armed Islamist group that locals refer to as 'Al Shabaab' clashed with government forces in the fishing village of Maluku, some 30 km from Mocimboa da Praia on 21 October. The attacks prompted the villagers to flee.

actor2: ASWJ-Mozambique: Ahlu Sunna Wal Jamaa (Mozambique faction)
notes: Clashes reported in the village of Columbe on 22 October. Armed men attacked a building in Mocimboa da Praia. They are suspected of being the same ones that had already attacked the locality before who are referred to as 'Al Shabaab'.

actor2: ASWJ-Mozambique: Ahlu Sunna Wal Jamaa (Mozambique faction)
notes: The Mozambican police regains control of the territory after the attack in Mocimboa da Praia.

Property destruction: Armed men, believed to be Islamic militants, attacked Ulumbi in Palma. The attack targeted a building. The incident followed another clash that had taken place in Palma and during which 11 people were captured and handed to the police. The armed men are suspected of being affiliated with the people who perpetrated the attacks in Mocimboa da Praia.
On March 3, an unknown group of armed men attacked Chitolo, in Mocimboa da Praia, killing one person and burning several houses.

actor1: ASWJ-Mozambique: Ahlu Sunna Wal Jamaa (Mozambique faction)
source: Agencia de Informacao de Mocambique; Voa Portugues
notes: An Islamist militia attacked again on December 17th the locality of Mocimboa da Praia. The head of reconnaissance of the riot police was killed and five other police members were severely injured. The column was ambushed on its way to resupply the police unit at Mitumbate, one of the villages in Mocimboa da Praia that has come under attack. The rebels blocked the road, and when the police left their vehicles to remove the obstacles, the attackers opened fire. This clash comes three days after the General Commander of the police gave the islamist insurgents an ultimatum.

actor1: ASWJ-Mozambique: Ahlu Sunna Wal Jamaa (Mozambique faction)
source: Agencia de Informacao de Mocambique; Club of Mozambique
notes: On April 15, an islamist milita attacked the village of Ncumbi, in Palma district. The group, made up of 10 men, with 1 carrying a machine gun and the other carrying machetes, started the raid at 1am, seeking food. They targeted one stall and burned it down after the man who owned it refused to open the store. They killed this man. Then they continued their attack, targeting other stores. The attack came on the final day of a visit to Cabo Delgado by President Filipe Nyusi.

actor1: ASWJ-Mozambique: Ahlu Sunna Wal Jamaa (Mozambique faction)
notes: Movement of forces: On 21 March suspected Islamist militants who perpetrated attacks in Mocimboa da Praia were sighted in the banks of river Quinhevo, in Cabo Delgado.
Immigrants reported having been beaten and raped in a crackdown on "illegal" immigrants by the Mozambican police. A man was pushed off a bus by the police and run over.

actor1: ASWJ-Mozambique: Ahlu Sunna Wal Jamaa (Mozambique faction)
source: Voa Portugues; Agencia de Informacao de Mocambique
notes: Another attack took place this week, on January 16th, in the district of Nangade. The event, which resulted in the death of a nurse and another civilian, as well as injuries to another civilian, is suspected to have been perpetrated by an Islamist militia. The attackers are reported to have also stolen 8 bikes.

source: Agencia de Informacao de Mocambique; Pretoria News
notes: Community police beat up Renamo party members who were holding a meeting. The local office of Renamo was set on fire.

actor1: ASWJ-Mozambique: Ahlu Sunna Wal Jamaa (Mozambique faction)
notes: On April 21, an Islamist militia attacked the village of Mangwaza, in Palma district.They killed one person, burned four houses and stole food. Attacks unconfirmed by police.

actor1: ASWJ-Mozambique: Ahlu Sunna Wal Jamaa (Mozambique faction)
notes: On April 20, an Islamist milita attacked Diaca Velha, close to the border with Nangade in Cabo Delgado. The attackers stole food and killed a number of people. Casualties are unconfirmed. Attacks unconfirmed by police.

actor2: ASWJ-Mozambique: Ahlu Sunna Wal Jamaa (Mozambique faction)
notes: Agreement: On 21 March, a group of Islamist militiamen carrying out attacks in Mocimboa da Praia surrendered to the defense forces.

Angry mobs attacked healthcare centres and public officials in Macomia district (no precise date given) over allegations that healthcare workers and FRELIMO party officials were contributing to the spread of a cholera outbreak.
2 policemen were severely beaten and 1 taken prisoner after villagers angry about a drug raid ambushed them.
About 100 people demonstrated at the police station following the shooting of an unarmed man

On February 19th, a woman was condemned to being whipped five times over offering 'social and political insults' in the neighbourhood 30 de junho, in Mocimboa. Local authorities forced the punishment on the woman; local police has not yet released a statement.

actor1: ASWJ-Mozambique: Ahlu Sunna Wal Jamaa (Mozambique faction)
source: Voa Portugues; Xinhua; Agencia de Informacao de Mocambique
notes: On January 13th, an armed group attacked the administrative post of Olumbi, in Palma, and opened fire on the Government structures, killing 5 people. Civilian testimonies state that the stalls in the local market were burned, as well as the headquarters of the adiministrative post vandalised. Later reports mention that the police suspects the assailants of belonging to an Islamist militia. The 5 deaths were confirmed; 11 other people were injured, 8 of them seriously.

Unknown armed people killed on Wednesday the secretary of the municipal neighbourhood of Nanchemele in Mocimboa da Praia. According to testimonies, 5 men broke into his house with knives and stabbed him in the neck.
10 Renamo gunmen attacked a police post, killing the head of the police station. When the police returned fire, the gunmen left.

actor1: ASWJ-Mozambique: Ahlu Sunna Wal Jamaa (Mozambique faction)
source: Voa Portugues; Xinhua; Shabelle Media Network (Mogadishu); Chatam House
notes: 30 armed men associated to an Islamist fundamentalist group assaulted three police stations in Mocimboa da Praia. 2 police officers were killed, alongside 14 members of the armed group killed. 1 or 2 of the armed men were captured. Reports of civilians killed also erupted, but with unconfirmed numbers. The attack lasted two days.

A group of unidentified men armed with machetes and other blunt instruments attacked the village of Inlane in the district of Palma, Cabo Delgado province, early on Friday morning 12th. 2 people died and 2 others were injured. A group of women were also abducted to help carry the supplies looted in homes and commercial establishments.
